you're really interested in doing. I see Marcos adding support to that with a reaction. Mike,

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:54.920
do you have anything to add on to that, like getting started with contributing?

00:22:54.920 --> 00:23:02.040
From a management standpoint, do you allow people to have a certain amount of time in their day or

00:23:02.040 --> 00:23:06.839
in their week or month to contribute back to open source? Or does it need to be really focused on

00:23:06.839 --> 00:23:11.959
problems that Flatiron is solving? Yeah, it's a tough one, right? We're

00:23:11.959 --> 00:23:16.359
all busy with our day jobs, and the question is, where do you focus your energy always?

00:23:16.920 --> 00:23:23.079
And we generally try to, I don't want to say limit, but focus on, would this be critical for

00:23:23.079 --> 00:23:27.959
us to be able to move forward again? Because we're a fairly lean team. We don't have a lot of latitude

00:23:27.959 --> 00:23:35.160
to carve out as much free capacity as we would likely like. And so we've tried to be intentional

00:23:35.160 --> 00:23:40.520
around, let's say we're doing a big migration, a snowflake, this isn't really helpful to do this,

00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:45.319
then it's also a great opportunity for someone like Anthony or me or Erica to jump in and try

00:23:45.319 --> 00:23:50.920
to solve that problem, not only on behalf of us, but also others who may encounter this problem

00:23:50.920 --> 00:23:56.439
going forward. So I think it's like, when we need to, we definitely are willing to,

00:23:56.439 --> 00:24:04.040
